{"title_page": "Hussein Ibish", "text_new": "'''Hussein Yusuf Kamal Ibish''' ([[Arabic Language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0643\u0645\u0627\u0644 \u0623\u064a\u0628\u0634) ({{IPAc-en|a\u026a|b|\u026a|\u0283}}) (born 1963) is a Senior Resident Scholar at [[The Arab Gulf States Institute]] in Washington.<ref>http://www.agsiw.org/associates/hussein-ibish/</ref>  He was a Fellow at the former [[American Task Force on Palestine]].<ref>[http://www.americantaskforce.org/staff/hussein_ibish American Task Force on Palestine]. Retrieved 2011-03-31.</ref> He has a [[Ph.D.]] in [[Comparative literature]] from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]<ref>[http://scholarworks.umass.edu/dissertations/AAI3039364/ Dissertation: Nationalism as an Ethical Problem for Postcolonial Theory.  Chair: Dr. David Lenson.]</ref> and is active in advocacy for Arab causes in the [[United States]]. He is a weekly columnist for [[NOW Lebanon]]. He describes himself as an agnostic from the Muslim-American community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibishblog.com/blog/hibish/2009/09/21/why_agnostic_and_secularist_fights_american_muslim_rights_and_against_islamop |title= Why an agnostic and secularist fights for American Muslim rights and against Islamophobia |accessdate=2010-09-16 |first=Hussein |last=Ibish |date=September 21, 2009 |work=Ibishblog |quote=...I am, and have ... been a committed agnostic...from the Muslim American community and part of the Muslim American community.}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nIbish was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]].{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} He comes from an academic background.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} His father, Yusuf Ibish, studied at [[Harvard University|Harvard University's]] Department of Government in the 1950s and was on the faculty of the [[American University of Beirut]] as a scholar of [[Islam]]. His father and mother were devout Sunni Muslim and Anglican Christian, respectively, although he never embraced either religion.<ref>{{cite news|author1=HUSSEIN IBISH|title=Who Is a Muslim?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/15/opinion/who-is-a-muslim.html|accessdate=30 June 2017|work=The New York Times|date=15 Dec 2015}}</ref> Ibish attended [[Emerson College]], earning a bachelor of science degree in mass communications in 1986.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} He has a PhD in comparative literature from the University of Massachusetts Amherst.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\n==Career==\n*Communications Director for the [[American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee]] (ADC), 1998\u20132004<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=858753 \"\"All Things Considered\" interview, November 26, 2002.] Retrieved 2011-03-31.</ref><ref>[http://discuss.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/zforum/03/sp_iraq_ibish040903.htm Online discussion, April 9, 2003.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080319111352/http://discuss.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/zforum/03/sp_iraq_ibish040903.htm |date=March 19, 2008 }} Retrieved 2011-03-31.</ref>\n*Founding member of the [[Progressive Muslim Union]] (later resigned)<ref>[http://www.amperspective.com/html/pmu_resignations.html Progressive Muslim Union: Three founding members resign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061006105922/http://www.amperspective.com/html/pmu_resignations.html |date=2006-10-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date= May 2018}}\n* ''What's Wrong with the One-State Agenda? Why Ending the Occupation and Peace with Israel is Still the Palestinian National Goal''. American Task Force for Palestine (ATFP), 2009\n* \"Hate Crimes and Discrimination against Arab Americans 1998-2000\". American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee (ADC), 2001)\n* \"Hate Crimes and Discrimination Against Arab-Americans Sept. 11, 2001-Oct. 11, 2002\" (ADC, 2003)\n* \"Report on Hate Crimes and Discrimination against Arab Americans: 2003-2007\" (ADC, 2008)\n* \"At the Constitution's Edge: Arab Americans and Civil Liberties in the United States\" in ''States of Confinement: Policing, Detention, and Prisons'', Joy James, ed. New York: St. Martin's Press, 2000\n* \"Anti-Arab Bias in American Policy and Discourse\" in ''Race in 21st Century America'', Curtis Stokes, Theresa Melendez, Genice Rhodes-Reed, eds. East Lansing: Michigan State University Press, 2001\n* \"Race and the War on Terror\" in ''Race and Human Rights'', Curtis Stokes, ed. Michigan State University Press, 2005\n* \"Symptoms of Alienation: How Arab and American Media View Each Other\" in ''Arab Media in the Information Age''. ECSSR, 2005\n* \"The Palestinian Right of Return\" (ADC, 2001)\n* \"The Media and the New Intifada\" in ''The New Intifada'', Roane Carey, ed. Verso, 2001\n* Editor, ''Principles and Pragmatism''. ATFP, 2006\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{External links|date=April 2016}}\n*[http://www.ibishblog.com/ IbishBlog] ''official blog''\n*[http://www.americantaskforce.org/staff/hussein_ibish Profile] at [[The American Task Force on Palestine]]\n*{{C-SPAN|husseinibish}}\n*{{IMDb name|1742084}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-no2001-77927}}\n;Interview and articles\n*[http://colorlines.com/article.php?ID=194 Q&A - Hussein Ibish by Judith LeBlanc (Colorlines)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080503132019/http://www.adc.org/action/2002/26March2002.htm Ibish Responds to Daniel Pipes in New York Post]\n*[http://www.adc.org/index.php?id=2118 Ibish vs. Jerry Falwell on CNN's Crossfire]\n*[https://www.usatoday.com/community/chat/2002-01-18-ibish.htm Arab-Americans after 9/11: Hussein Ibish (USA Today)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080319095548/http://www.commondreams.org/cgi-bin/print.cgi?file=%2Fviews01%2F1129-07.htm What went wrong in Arab world? America, ask yourself (LA Times)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010630233002/http://www.nigelparry.com/issues/shamir/ The Israel Shamir Case]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070410093057/http://counterpunch.org/ibish0917.html The Shoney's Incident: Determine the Truth Behind False Alarm]\n*[http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0206/05/cf.00.html CNN CROSSFIRE - Israel Retaliates to Suicide Bombing by Invading Arafat Compound]\n*[http://www.wrmea.com/archives/junejuly2002/0206082.html Ibish/Herschensohn Debate at Nixon Library Challenges Outdated Israeli Myths]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928113640/http://www.themichiganjournal.com/home/index.cfm?event=displayArticle&ustory_id=269158f2-e84b-4211-8133-f5bb71cee97d Media watchdog Ibish visits UM-D to speak against Iraq war]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050113091416/http://cnnstudentnews.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0110/25/cf.00.html Target Terrorism: Forcing Suspects to Talk (CNN CROSSFIRE)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140809062609/http://www.fathomjournal.org/policy-politics/obamas-second-term-two-views-on-the-peace-process-view-two/ Obama's second term: two views on the Peace Process - view two], [http://www.fathomjournal.org/ Fathom: For a better understanding of Israel and the region], 30 January 2013\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibish, Hussein}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:American writers of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Emerson College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Amherst alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Beirut]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Lebanese descent]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hussein Yusuf Kamal Ibish''' ([[Arabic Language|Arabic]]: \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0643\u0645\u0627\u0644 \u0623\u064a\u0628\u0634) ({{IPAc-en|a\u026a|b|\u026a|\u0283}}) (1963 -) is a Senior Resident Scholar at [[The Arab Gulf States Institute]] in Washington.<ref>http://www.agsiw.org/associates/hussein-ibish/</ref>  He was a Fellow at the former [[American Task Force on Palestine]].<ref>[http://www.americantaskforce.org/staff/hussein_ibish American Task Force on Palestine]. Retrieved 2011-03-31.</ref> He has a [[Ph.D.]] in [[Comparative literature]] from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]<ref>[http://scholarworks.umass.edu/dissertations/AAI3039364/ Dissertation: Nationalism as an Ethical Problem for Postcolonial Theory.  Chair: Dr. David Lenson.]</ref> and is active in advocacy for Arab causes in the [[United States]]. He is a weekly columnist for [[NOW Lebanon]]. He describes himself as an agnostic from the Muslim-American community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibishblog.com/blog/hibish/2009/09/21/why_agnostic_and_secularist_fights_american_muslim_rights_and_against_islamop |title= Why an agnostic and secularist fights for American Muslim rights and against Islamophobia |accessdate=2010-09-16 |first=Hussein |last=Ibish |date=September 21, 2009 |work=Ibishblog |quote=...I am, and have ... been a committed agnostic...from the Muslim American community and part of the Muslim American community.}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nIbish was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]].{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} He comes from an academic background.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} His father, Yusuf Ibish, studied at [[Harvard University|Harvard University's]] Department of Government in the 1950s and was on the faculty of the [[American University of Beirut]] as a scholar of [[Islam]]. His father and mother were devout Sunni Muslim and Anglican Christian, respectively, although he never embraced either religion.<ref>{{cite news|author1=HUSSEIN IBISH|title=Who Is a Muslim?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/15/opinion/who-is-a-muslim.html|accessdate=30 June 2017|work=The New York Times|date=15 Dec 2015}}</ref> Ibish attended [[Emerson College]], earning a bachelor of science degree in mass communications in 1986.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}} He has a PhD in comparative literature from the University of Massachusetts Amherst.{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\n==Career