{"title_page": "Great Northwest Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA conference tournament\n| name               = Great Northwest Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament\n| optional_subheader = Conference Basketball Championship\n| defunct            =\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| sport              = [[Basketball]]\n| conference         = [[Great Northwest Athletic Conference]]\n| number_of_teams    = 6\n| format             = [[Single-elimination tournament]]\n| current_stadium    = [[Sam Carver Gymnasium]]\n| current_location   = [[Bellingham, Washington]]\n| years              = 2011\u2013present\n| most_recent        = \n| current_champion   = [[Western Washington Vikings|Western Washington]] (2nd)\n| most_championships = Seattle Pacific (4)\n| television         = \n| website            = [http://www.gnacsports.com/mbasketball/ GNAC men's basketball]\n| sponsors           =\n| all_stadiums       = '''Royal Brougham Pavilion''' (2020)<br>Sam Carver Gymnasium (2019)<br> [[Alaska Airlines Center]](2018)<br>Marcus Pavilion (2012\u20132017)\n| all_locations      = '''[[Seattle, Washington]]''' (2020)<br>[[Bellingham, Washington]] (2019)<br> [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage, AK]] (2018)<br>[[Lacey, Washington|Lacey, WA]] (2012\u20132017)\n}}\n\nThe '''Great Northwest Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament''' is the annual conference [[basketball]] championship tournament for the [[Great Northwest Athletic Conference]]. The tournament has been held annually since 2011. It is a [[single-elimination tournament]] and seeding is based on regular season records.<ref>{{cite web | title = GNAC Men's Basketball Tournament History | work = Year-by-year records | publisher = GNAC | year = 2016 | url = http://www.gnacsports.com/media/MBasketball/Record%20Book/AllTimeStandingsMBB.pdf | accessdate = February 22, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060310/http://www.gnacsports.com/media/MBasketball/Record%20Book/AllTimeStandingsMBB.pdf | archive-date = March 4, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nThe winner, declared conference champion, receives the conference's automatic bid to the [[NCAA Men's Division II Basketball Championship]].\n\n==Tournament format==\nSince its establishment in 2011, the GNAC tournament began as an 8-team tournament but has since decreased in size to six teams. The eight-team tournament, played during 2011 and 2012, featured all teams contesting the initial quarterfinal. Meanwhile, the six-team tournament, played since 2013, gave the two top-seeded teams a bye into the semifinals while the remaining teams played in the preliminary quarterfinal round. \n\nAside from the inaugural tournament in 2011 which was played only on team campuses, the remaining tournaments have been played at Marcus Pavilion on the campus of [[Saint Martin's Saints|Saint Martin's University]] in [[Lacey, Washington]].\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Champions\n!Score\n!Runner-Up\n!MVP\n!Venue\n|- align=center\n| 2011\n| '''[[Central Washington Wildcats men's basketball|Central Washington]]'''\n| 83\u201371\n| [[Alaska Anchorage Seawolves men's basketball|Alaska Anchorage]]\n| Jamar Berry, Central Washington\n| Nicholson Pavilion ([[Ellensburg, Washington|Ellensburg, WA]])\n|- align=center\n| 2012\n| '''[[Montana State Billings Yellowjackets|Montana State Billings]]'''\n| 74\u201370\n| Alaska Anchorage\n| Robert Mayes, Montana State Billings\n| Marcus Pavilion ([[Lacey, Washington|Lacey, WA]])\n|- align=center\n| 2013\n| '''[[Seattle Pacific Falcons|Seattle Pacific]]'''\n| 72\u201370\n| [[Western Washington Vikings|Western Washington]]\n| David Downs, Seattle Pacific\n| Marcus Pavilion ([[Lacey, Washington|Lacey, WA]])\n|- align=center\n| 2014\n| '''Seattle Pacific'''\n| 65\u201362\n| Western Washington\n| David Downs (2), Seattle Pacific\n| Marcus Pavilion ([[Lacey, Washington|Lacey, WA]])\n|- align=center\n| 2015\